description.text:
We designed this simple print to convert the standard Stanley or retracting knife blade into a handy print removal tool. If your printing onto a tape bed then you will know how some parts are too fragile or have a difficult lip / skirt to get under. This tool gives you loads of control to apply lots of pressure but in a controlled way.
You need to take care with the blade. Many people use some kind of spatula, however you don't really have much control. We tested this and it works great for small and larger parts where you need to start working an edge.
We recommend you don't make this if your at school unless your able to do this attended by an adult.
First Dull the blade with emery paper and ensure the ends are in the correct orientation. If it seems like it doesn't fit, flip the blade over as their is only one way this fits. Ensure you have knocked the thumb tools onto the ends well before use and always keep downward pressure with both hands, in a forward and rocking motion. this tool works really well, however we accept no liability for injury. Go carefull! Build recommendation as per Cura shot. Build on its side with max layer 0.1. Min Fill %30.

comments.text: Hey, glad you like it! Yeah, to give you a basic rundown of my workflow, I made this in a free program called Sculptris, which is great for organics. The sword and base came from TinkerCAD, which I can't recommend too highly. Both of these programs have their strengths, though I feel that, in combination, there isn't really anything you can't do. I combined/staged the parts in MakerBot Desktop and saved the model as an STL. Then, to make it solid/fix internal geometries, I ran the model through Netfabb. This is how I make most of my character models, though I use different degrees of Sculptris and TinkerCAD depending on the piece (some robots and vehicles I do entirely through TinkerCAD). Hope this was helpful! If you make some stuff, I'd love to see it.

This is (what I call) a 'leveling block' for a NGP (No Ground Plane) Side Mount Firestik CB Antenna. My truck cap (Jason brand) is angled and not straight (up) and so in order for me to mount my antenna so it is level and not mounted at the same angle as the cap side, I created this leveling block to account for the angle and get the antenna mounted plumb. Included is the original 123d Design file so you may modify as you desire and of course the STL file. I printed this with the flat side down and with 100% infill for strength. The design is for Firestik brand side mount CB Antennas (http://www.rightchannelradios.com/collections/no-ground-plane-cb-antennas/products/firestik-ngp-antenna-side-mount-kit-right-channel-radios-1).

When I mount it I plan on using stainless machine screws and I will put an aluminum back plate inside the cap and bolt it all in with nylon lock nuts. Again...when I do the work, I will update the photos.

description.text:
This project is a lesson in Mendelian genetics for an 8th grade class. Original concept by Dr. Pamela Esprivalo Harrell in the January 1997 issue of Science Scope. The original activity used pieces of paper to make a dragon.

Part one of the activity Dragon Genetics is focused on Mendelian genetics - genotypes, phenotypes, dominant and recessive alleles.

Part two of the activity Dragon Breeding included drawing Punnet squares.

The activity also introduces incomplete dominance in the form of the dragon body color. You can easily adapt the activity to use just 2 body colors, or eliminate that as a trait altogether and print all the models in the same color.

Dragon models inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5236, and created with help from the art teacher (I can't draw). In this activity the model is copied, mirrored, and flipped to make the reverse side. The two pieces are then glued together.

The models are thick enough to stand on their own without gluing on the reverse side.
NGSS

Objective

This activity is intended to reinforce these points

  • Each trait is determined by two factors called genes
  • You inherit one gene for each trait from each parent
  • The different forms of a gene are called alleles
  • Some alleles are dominant, some are recessive. A dominant allele overpowers a recessive one if both are present
  • The combination of genes is called a genotype
  • Genotypes can be homozygous / purebred (both alleles the same) or heterozygous / hybrid (alleles are different)
  • The observable trait caused by the combination of alleles is called a Phenotype
Preparation

This project is intended to be part of a unit on genetics and heredity.

Before beginning the activity download the Dragon Genetics PDF and make copies for the student. Or copy it from Google Docs - https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gJFkw7j4BTVxqDdKa7M6ZXxIHoV5WMvjzglo4uDB8pM/edit?usp=sharing

Download and print the Dragon Chromosomes PDF or copy from Google Docs - https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NttirXMCrUwSjEeomqXPG_EI-cnPNvE5Bpp3_FTaq44/edit?usp=sharing I print the male chromosomes on blue paper and the female chromosomes on pink paper.

Each student will need a male and female set of chromosomes. I like to put them inside plastic Easter eggs. You can get the eggs dirt cheap after Easter.

Steps
  1. Copy the genes from the female and male chromosomes onto your workshop. Dominant alleles should be written before recessive ones.
  2. Use the key to determine the phenotype for each trait.
  3. Make up a name for your dragon.
  4. Login to Tinkercad and open the Dragon Genetics Construction Kit. Or Download the pieces you will need from Thingiverse.
  5. Build your dragon according to math your phenotypes. Make sure all the pieces are solidly connected (rotate the model and look carefully to be sure).
  6. Delete all the extra pieces you didn't need.
  7. Duplicate your dragon model, mirror it through the X-Y plane, then flip 180 degrees to make the reverse side.
  8. Download and print your dragon model in the correct color plastic
  9. Glue the pieces together
Results

This project was completed with two 8th grade science classes. The students were able to complete the lab report and their dragon models in one class period (45 minutes).

Problems with the 3D models were the usual - not completely connecting the pieces, leaving a small gap between them.

A selection of models created by the students are included here.

Objective

This is a follow up to the Dragon Genetics activity that includes selective breeding and drawing Punnet Squares

Preparation

You need a group of male and female dragons for the students to choose from. I used the dragon models the students created in the Dragon Genetics activity for the gene pool. Male and female dragons were put on separate tables with a list of their genotypes. In a pinch you could just have the genotypes of the dragons available without the models.

Download and print the Dragon Breeding PDF or copy if from Google Docs - https://docs.google.com/document/d/1kTZwuXVlfcqvkui6_cIJQmMW4YiuKyi5xA6jdrJWPts/edit?usp=sharing

Steps
  1. Decide what trait(s) you'd like in your baby dragon.
  2. Make a plan for how you will choose the mother and father dragon that will have the best chance of created a baby with the trait(s) you want.
  3. Choose a mother and father dragon, copy their genotypes onto your worksheet
  4. Use coin flips to determine which gene you inherit from each parent for each trait
  5. Use the key to determine the phenotypes of your baby dragon.
  6. Make up a name for your dragon.
  7. Login to Tinkercad and open the Dragon Genetics Construction Kit. Or Download the pieces you will need from Thingiverse.
  8. Build your dragon according to math your phenotypes. Make sure all the pieces are solidly connected (rotate the model and look carefully to be sure).
  9. Delete all the extra pieces you didn't need.
  10. Duplicate your dragon model, mirror it through the X-Y plane, then flip 180 degrees to make the reverse side.
  11. Download and print your dragon model in the correct color plastic
  12. Glue the pieces together
Results

This project was completed successfully with two 8th grade science classes. Print the models ast50% or 75% for cute little baby dragons.

The original design has a very good connection to the microscope. So while making picture or films the image stays very sharp. But the adapter is not suitable to new phones with a better camera, which are thinner and have there buttons on the side of the phone. I used an older microscope with a tube of 30 mm. So i made some modifications to fit the situation.
The pictures are from the first attempt with the original design with 30mm clamps and an other phone.

Changed size for the microscope connection to 30 mm
The body and the clamp are connected, so no glue is required.
Changed position of the slider for samsung S6 with the buttons on the side.
Changed the height of the sliders adapted to a thin phone.
add some wingnut adapters M3 for easy operation. The wingnut adapter has to be used with a M3 ring to lift the wings from the surface.
